<h1>Problem 970 - 2006 China TST Day 1, P3 of 3, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Find all positive integer pairs \((a,n)\) such that \[\frac{(a+1)^{n}-a^{n}}{n}\] is an integer.</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class=skib>
<p>Suppose a prime \(p \mid n\) and \(p \mid a\), then \(p \mid a+1\) as well, which is not possible. So \(\gcd(a, n) = \gcd(a+1, n) = 1\). 
\[(a + 1)^n \equiv a^n \pmod{n} \implies (1 + a^{-1})^n \equiv 1 \pmod{n}\] 
So the order divides \(\gcd(n, \phi(n))\) which is very mid. Wait actually choose the smallest prime \(q \mid n\), from which we get 
\[(1 + a^{-1})^n \equiv 1 \pmod{q}\]
Except now note that the order must divide \(\gcd(q - 1, n)\) which has to be \(1\) due to the smallest prime play (dynamic think). This means \(a^{-1} \equiv 0 \pmod{q}\) - and this is not possible, so \(n = 1\) must hold, in which case all \(a\) work.</p>
</div>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Love primes like you love your water. Dynamic think your way to smallest prime even though it is standard tech.</p>
